p.gov.br/livros/pdfs/artesplasticas.pdf GUIMAR\u00c3ES, Andr\u00e9a Camargo... (et al.) ''Cronologia de artes pl\u00e1sticas : refer\u00eancias 1975-1995'' \u2013 S\u00e3o Paulo : Centro Cultural S\u00e3o Paulo-IDART, 2010.]\n* [http://www.gretta.info/reviews_incremento.html KLINTOWITZ, Jacob. Uma viagem pelo ego de Gretta Sarfaty. Jornal da Tarde, S\u00e3o Paulo, 14 March 1988. N\u00e3o catalogado]\n* [http://www.gretta.info/reviews_astrivingtolove.html LODA, Romana. Gretta: um tentativo de amor. Galleria Multimedia (Brescia), 1981.]\n*MAGALH\u00c3ES, Fabio. Ousadias, afetos e mem\u00f3rias. Texto para exposi\u00e7\u00e3o e cat\u00e1logo Reconcilia\u00e7\u00f5es no IAB \u2013 Instituto dos Arquitetos do Brasil, 2020.\n* [http://www.gretta.info/review_libriste.html Marco Carminati, Dino Silvestroni, Marta Zocchi, ''Libriste dalla Collezione di Libri d\u2019Artista di Marco Carminati'', introduction by: Ada de Pirro, Instituzione Biblioteca Classense, Ravenna, March 2012.]\n* [http://www.gretta.info/review_independent_news.html Mike Higgins, ''Gretta: Reflections of a Woman'', in: Independent Newspaper London, December 1997.]\n* PANORAMA DE ARTE ATUAL BRASILEIRA, S\u00e3o Paulo, 1976. Pintura. Apresenta\u00e7\u00e3o de Paulo Mendes de Almeida. S\u00e3o Paulo: MAM, 1976.\n*SILVEIRA, Paulo. ''A p\u00e1gina violada, da ternura \u00e0 inj\u00faria na constru\u00e7\u00e3o do livro de artista''. Editora da UFRGS, Porto Alegre, RS, Brasil, 2008.\n* PO\u00c9TICAS visuais. Apresenta\u00e7\u00e3o de Walter Zanini. Texto de J\u00falio Plaza. S\u00e3o Paulo: MAC/USP, 1977.\n* Mini-doc em 3 partes sobre a trajet\u00f3ria de Gretta Sarfaty: ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JyrIjyc3Fx8 Gretta's Progress I]''; ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Qj819WyKX7Q Gretta's Progress II]''; ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UOGZ9CmGiEU Gretta's Progress III]''.\n*[http://mam.org.br/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/MAM70_CATALOGO_Completo_baixa.pdf Exhibition Catalogue MAM and MAC: 70 Years.]\n*[http://www.teses.usp.br/teses/disponiveis/48/48134/tde-03122018-121223/pt-br.php TRIZOLI, Talita. Atravessamentos feministas: Um panorama de mulheres artistas no Brasil dos anos 60/70. Tese de Doutorado, 2018.]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20190430175216/http://revistaerrata.gov.co/contenido/traves-de-un-espejo-subjetivaciones-femeninas-en-el-arte-brasileno-de-los-anos-setenta TRIZOLI, Talita. A trav\u00e9s de um espejo: subjetivaciones femeninas en el arte brasile\u00f1o de los a\u00f1os setenta. Revista Errata#17, Colombia, 2017.]\n*[http://www.gretta.info/reviews_g7.html VERZOTTI, Giorgio. ''Gretta / Diagramma''. Magazine G7 Studio. It\u00e1lia, (Abril, 1979)]\n\n==Notes==\n<references group=\"n\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|gretta.info}}\n* [http://www.alegresarfatycollection.org Alegre Sarfaty Collection]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sarfaty, Gretta}}\n[[Category:British contemporary painters]]\n[[Category:English women painters]]\n[[Category:English curators]]\n[[Category:English people of Greek descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century British women artists]]\n[[Category:Women performance artists]]\n[[Category:Feminist artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women artists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSelected solo exhibitions:Typo fixing, replaced: venezulea \u2192 Venezuela", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gretta_Sarfaty"}
{"title_page": "Pierre Andr\u00e9 de Suffren", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n| name          = Pierre Andr\u00e9 de Suffren\n| image         = Suffren.jpg\n| caption       = Bust of Suffren by Houdon\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1729|07|17|df=yes}}\n| death_date          = {{Death date and age|1788|12|08|1729|07|17|df=yes}}\n| placeofburial_label =\n| placeofburial = Ashes defiled in 1793 by the Revolutionaries<ref>[http://www.polytechnique.fr/eleves/binets/xpassion/article.php?id=111&page=2 Les voyages du Bailli de Suffren] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081231193449/http://www.polytechnique.fr/eleves/binets/xpassion/article.php?id=111&page=2 |date=2008-12-31 }}</ref>\n| birth_place  =Ch\u00e2teau de [[Saint-Cannat]]\n| death_place  =[[Paris]]\n| placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n| nickname      = Jupiter<ref name=cunat382>Cunat, p.382</ref> \n|allegiance={{Flagicon image|Flag of the Sovereign Military Order of Malta.svg}} [[Sovereign Military Order of Malta]] <br/>{{flag|Kingdom of France}}\n| branch        = {{navy|Kingdom of France}}\n| serviceyears  = 1743\u20131784\n| rank          = [[Vice-admiral]] in the French Navy<br />\nGeneral of the Galley of Malta\n| unit          = Indian Ocean squadron\n| commands      =\n| battles       =\n[[War of the Austrian Succession]]: \n*[[Battle of Toulon (1744)|Battle of Toulon]]\n*[[Second Battle of Cape Finisterre (1747)|Battle of Cape Finisterre]]\n[[Seven Years' War]]:\n*[[Battle of Minorca (1756)|Battle of Minorca]]\n*[[Battle of Lagos]]\n[[Anglo-French War 1779|Anglo-French War]]:\n*[[Battle of Porto Praya]]\n*[[Battle of Grenada]]\n*[[Battle of Sadras]]\n*[[Battle of Providien]]\n*[[Battle of Negapatam (1782)|Battle of Negapatam]]\n*[[Battle of Trincomalee]]\n*[[Battle of Cuddalore (1783)|Battle of Cuddalore]]\n*[[Siege of Cuddalore]]\n| awards        = [[File:Ordre du Saint-Esprit Chevalier ribbon.svg|35px]] [[Order of the Holy Spirit]] <br />\n[[Knights Hospitaller|Order of Saint-John of J\u00e9rusalem]]\n| relations     =\n| laterwork     =\n}}\n\n[[Admiral]] '''comte Pierre Andr\u00e9 de Suffren de Saint Tropez, bailli de Suffren''' {{refn|usually pronounced {{IPA|[syf\u0281\u025bn]}}, historically {{IPA|[syf\u0281\u025b\u0303]}} and still pronounced in this way in the French Navy<ref name=monaque2009-2>Monaque, ''Suffren'' (2009), p.2, also cited at [https://troisponts.net/2019/03/25/suffren-suffene-ou-suffrin/]</ref>|group=Note}} (17 July 1729 \u2013 [[Paris]], 8 December 1788<ref name=hennequin289>Hennequin, p.289</ref>), Ch\u00e2teau de [[Saint-Cannat]]) was a [[France|French]] Navy officer and [[admiral]]. Beginning his career during the [[War of the Austrian Succession]], he fought in the [[Seven Years' War]], where he was taken prisoner at the [[Battle of Lagos]]. Promoted to Captain in 1772, he was one of the aids of [[Charles Henri Hector d'Estaing|Admiral d'Estaing]] during the [[Naval battles of the American Revolutionary War]], notably taking part in the [[Siege of Savannah]].\n\nSuffren was then appointed to serve in the [[Indian Ocean]] under [[Thomas d'Estienne d'Orves]], but assumed command himself at his death. Leading a 15-ship squadron, he fought five intense and evenly matched battles for [[Command of the sea|supremacy]] against Vice-Admiral Sir [[Edward Hughes (admiral)|Edward Hughes]]. Allied to [[Hyder Ali]], Suffren managed to challenge the established British power in Indian until the end of the war.\n\nAt his return, he was promoted to Vice-Admiral. He died shortly before he was to take command of the Brest squadron of the French fleet.\n\n== Biography ==\n===Early life===\nPierre Andr\u00e9 de Suffren was born on 17 July 1729 in the Ch\u00e2teau de [[Saint-Cannat]] to the family of Marquis [[Paul de Suffren]], the third son of an old nobility from [[Provence]] with two daughters and three other sons.<ref name=cunat3>Cunat, p.3</ref> <ref>[http://gw.geneanet.org/pierfit?lang=en;p=paul;n=de+suffren Geneanet: Paul de Suffren]</ref> {{refn|The older son was an Army officer; the second, a priest; the third and fourth sons were Navy officers; the oldest daughter married Marquis de Pierrevert, and the youngest married Marquis de Nibles de Vitrolles.<ref>Cunat, p.2\u20143</ref>|group=Note}} In October 1743, as the [[War of the Austrian Succession]] was raging, Suffren, aged 14,<ref name=cunat3 /> went to [[Toulon]] to undertaken naval studies as a [[Gardes de la Marine|Garde-Marine]].<ref name=hennequin289 /> However, he spent only 6 months ashore before he was appointed on a ship.<ref>Monaque, ''A Precursor of Nelson'', p.85</ref>\n\n=== War of the Austrian Succession===\nSuffren served on the 64-gun [[French ship Solide (1722)|''Solide'']]<ref name=cunat3 /> and took part in the [[Battle of Toulon (1744)|Battle of Toulon]] in 1744. During the battle, ''Solide'' engaged [[HMS Northumberland (1705)|HMS ''Northumberland'']]. <ref name=cunat9>Cunat, p.9</ref>\n\nIn the spring of 1745, Suffren transferred on ''Pauline'', part of a 5-ship and 2-frigate squadron under Captain [[Jean-Baptiste Mac Nemara]],{{refn|Alternatively spelt \"Macn\u00e9mara\", \"Macnemara\"<ref name=cunat10 /> or \"Macnamara\"|group=Note}} sent to America to harasse British forces.<ref name=cunat10>Cunat, p.10</ref>{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}. At his return, Suffren served on the 60-gun [[French ship Trident (1742)|''Trident'']], under Captain d'Estourmel, and took part in [[Duc d'Anville expedition]].<ref name=cunat11>Cunat, p.11</ref>\n\nSuffren graduated from the Gardes-Marine in 1747 as an Ensign,<ref name=hennequin289 /> and worked on commissioning the brand new [[74-gun]] [[HMS Monarch (1747)|''Monarque'']], under Captain La B\u00e9doy\u00e8re,<ref name=cunat12>Cunat, p.12</ref> in a squadron under [[Henri-Fran\u00e7ois des Herbiers, Marquis de l'Estendu\u00e8re|Des Herbiers de l'Estendu\u00e8re]].<ref>Monaque, ''A Precursor of Nelson'', p.86</ref> He took part in the [[Second Battle of Cape Finisterre (1747)|Second Battle of Cape Finisterre]] on 25 October 1747, where La B\u00e9doy\u00e8re was killed and ''Monarque'', badly damaged, was captured.<ref name=cunat15>Cunat, p.15</ref> Suffren was taken prisoner.<ref name=cunat18>Cunat, p.18</ref>\n\nThe [[Treaty of Aix-la-Chapelle (1748)|Treaty of Aix-la-Chapelle]] restoring peace, Suffren joined the [[Knights Hospitaller|Order of Malta]].<ref name=cunat19>Cunat, p.19</ref> He served in several commercial expeditions <ref name=hennequin290>Hennequin, p.290</ref> on galleys of the Order, escorting merchantmen and defending them against the depredation of the [[Barbary pirates|Barbary corsairs]].  In late 1754, Suffren departed Malta to return to Toulon.<ref name=cunat19 />\n\n===Seven Years' War===\n{{Main|Seven Years' War|France in the Seven Years War}}\nIn 1756, Suffren had returned to Toulon and had risen to [[Lieutenant (navy)|Lieutenant]]. At the outbreak of the [[Seven Years' War]], Suffren was appointed to the 64-gun [[French ship Orph\u00e9e (1750)|''Orph\u00e9e'']], part of a 12-ship squadron under [[Roland-Michel Barrin de La Galissoni\u00e8re|La Galissoni\u00e8re]] tasked with ferrying 12,000 men under [[Armand de Vignerot du Plessis|Mar\u00e9chal de Richelieu]] to strike [[Menorca]]. The squadron departed on 10 April, arriving on 17 and landing troops; the British garrison retreated to [[St. Philip's Castle]] and was forced to surrender after the [[Siege of Fort St Philip (1756)|Siege of Fort St Philip]].<ref name=cunat25>Cunat, p.25</ref> Patrolling between [[Menorca]] and [[Mallorca]] to prevent British relief to support Fort St. Philip, La Galissoni\u00e8re intercepted a 13-ship squadron under [[John Byng|Admiral Byng]], leading to the [[Battle of Minorca (1756)|Battle of Minorca]]. The British failed to break the French blockade, and Fort St. Philip fell on 29 July.<ref name=cunat26>Cunat, p.26</ref>\n\nIn 1757, Suffren transferred to the 80-gun [[French ship Oc\u00e9an (1756)|''Oc\u00e9an'']], flagship of a 6-ship and 2-frigate squadron under [[Jean-Fran\u00e7ois de La Clue-Sabran]]. The squadron departed Toulon in November, bound for Brest. On 7 December, it called [[Cartagena, Spain|Cartagena]] to resupply, and found itself blockaded by a British from under [[Henry Osborne (admiral)|Henry Osborne]]. <ref name=cunat26 /> A relief squadron under [[Michel-Ange Duquesne de Menneville|Duquesne de Menneville]] attempted to break the blockade, but was destroyed in the [[Battle of Cartagena (1758)|Battle of Cartagena]], as La Clue failed to [[Sortie (siege warfare)|sortie]]. Suffren witnessed the capture of [[HMS Foudroyant (1758)|''Foudroyant'']] and ''Orph\u00e9e'' on 28 February 1758. La Clue's squadron eventually returned to Toulon.<ref name=cunat27>Cunat, p.27</ref>\n\nToulon was blockaded by [[Edward Boscawen]]'s forces but, on 16 August 1758, La Clue seized an opportunity to make a sortie with 12 ships and 3 frigates. The frigate [[HMS Gibraltar (1754)|HMS ''Gibraltar'']] detected La Clue's squadron and reported to Boscawen, who moved to intercept.<ref name=cunat29>Cunat, p.29</ref> Meanwhile, the French squadron failed to maintain formation and scattered.<ref name=cunat30>Cunat, p.30</ref> In the ensuing [[Battle of Lagos]], ''Oc\u00e9an'' ran aground in Almadora Bay and was burnt by the British, in violation of neutrality laws,{{sfn|Willis|2009|p=761}}<ref name=Monaque-pon-87>Monaque, ''A Precursor of Nelson'', p.87</ref> while her crew was taken prisoner, including Suffren.<ref name=cunat31>Cunat, p.31</ref> <ref name=hennequin290>Hennequin, p.290</ref> He returned to France after several months and was left without employ at sea for several years.<ref name=cunat32>Cunat, p.32</ref>\n\n=== Interwar period ===\nOn the return of peace in 1763 Suffren intended again to do the service in the caravans which was required to qualify him to hold the high and lucrative posts of the Order. He was, however, named to the command of the 20-gun [[xebec]] ''Cam\u00e9l\u00e9on'',<ref name=cunat32 /> which he cruised against the [[Barbary pirates]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}<ref name=hennequin291>Hennequin, p.291</ref> Shortly thereafter, he transferred on ''Singe'', also a 20-gun xebec, part of a squadron under [[Louis Charles du Chaffault de Besn\u00e9]].<ref name=hennequin291 /> He took part in the [[Larache expedition]].<ref name=cunat32 /> In 1767, Suffren was promoted to [[frigate captain]] and called to Brest to serve on the 64-gun [[French ship Union (1763)|''Union'']], flagship of a squadron headed by [[Pierre-Claude Haudeneau de Breugnon]].<ref name=cunat33>Cunat, p.33</ref><ref name=hennequin291 />\n\nAfter the end of the expedition, Suffren returned to Malta to resume escort duty with the Order. He spent four years, rising from Knight to Commander. In February 1772, he was promoted to [[Captain (naval)|Captain]] in the French Navy, and returned to Toulon to take command of the 26-gun frigate [[French frigate Mignonne (1767)|''Mignonne'']]. He conducted two patrols in the Eastern Mediterranean. <ref name=cunat33 /><ref name=hennequin291 />\n\nIn 1776, [[Louis Charles du Chaffault de Besn\u00e9|Duchaffault]] appointed Suffren to the command of the 26-gun frigate [[French frigate Alcm\u00e8ne (1774)|''Alcm\u00e8ne'']]. She departed for a training cruise to drill new navy officers. <ref name=cunat33 />  From that time till the beginning of the [[War of American Independence]] he commanded vessels in the squadron of evolution which the French government had established for the purpose of training its officers. {{sfn|Chisholm|1911}} \n\n=== War of American independence ===\n{{Main|Franco-American alliance|Anglo-French War (1778\u20131783)|Naval battles of the American Revolutionary War}}\nTensions mounted between France and England in early 1778 in the context of the [[American Revolutionary War]], with the [[Action of 17 June 1778]] constituting a step up announcing the [[Anglo-French War (1778\u20131783)|Anglo-French War]]. Suffren was appointed to the fleet of [[Charles Hector, comte d'Estaing|Admiral d'Estaing]], leading a squadron comprising the 64-gun [[French ship Fantasque (1758)|''Fantasque'']], which he personally captained,<ref name=Monaque-pon-87 /> and the frigates [[French frigate Aimable (1776)|''Aimable'']], [[French frigate Chim\u00e8re (1758)|''Chim\u00e8re'']] and [[French frigate Engageante (1766)|''Engageante'']].<ref name=cunat37>Cunat, p.37</ref> The mission of his force was to support Franco-American efforts in the [[Battle of Rhode Island]] by striking a 5-frigate British squadron anchored in [[Narragansett Bay]], off [[Newport, Rhode Island|Newport]],<ref name=hennequin291 /> comprising [[HMS Juno (1757)|HMS ''Juno'']], [[French ship Vestale (1756)|''Flora'']], [[HMS Lark (1762)|''Lark'']], [[HMS Orpheus (1773)|''Orpheus'']] and [[HMS Cerberus (1758)|''Cerebus'']]. On 5 August 1778, Suffren entered the Bay and anchored next to the British, who cut their cables and scuttled their ships by fire to avoid capture.<ref name=cunat37 /><ref name=hennequin292>Hennequin, p.292</ref> The Royal Navy ended up having to destroy ten of their own vessels in all,<ref name=Hepper>Hepper (1994), p.52.</ref> including five frigates.<ref name=Monaque-pon-87 /><ref group=Note>The remains of the ''Cerberus'' are now part of a site listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]], the \"[[Wreck Sites of HMS Cerberus and HMS Lark|Wreck Sites of HMS ''Cerberus'' and HMS ''Lark'']].\"</ref>\n\nThe French fleet sailed to Martinique, where Suffren's squadron joined up with it, and from there to Grenada, leading to the [[Battle of Grenada]] on 6 July 1779. ''Fantasque'' was at the front of the vanguard, preceding the 74-gun [[French ship Z\u00e9l\u00e9 (1763)|''Z\u00e9l\u00e9'']].<ref name=Monaque-pon-87 /> When the two fleets came in contact, she came under fire from the 74-gun [[HMS Royal Oak (1769)|''Royal Oak'']] and the 70-gun [[HMS Boyne (1766)|''Boyne'']], sustaining 62 men killed or wounded.<ref name=cunat38>Cunat, p.38</ref>{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}} After the battle, Admiral d'Estaing sent Suffren with a 2-ship and 3-frigate division to secure the surrender of [[Carriacou and Petite Martinique|Carriacou]] and [[Union Island]].<ref name=cunat39>Cunat, p.39</ref>\n\nOn 7 September 1779, d'Estaing ordered Suffren to blockade the mouth of [[Savannah River]], as to cover the landing of French troops in support of the [[Siege of Savannah]], and prevent British ships from escaping. Suffren led the 64-gun [[French ship Art\u00e9sien|''Art\u00e9sien'']] and [[French ship Provence (1763)|''Provence'']], and the frigates [[French frigate Fortun\u00e9e (1777)|''Fortun\u00e9e'']], [[French frigate Blanche (1766)|''Blanche'']] and  [[French frigate Chim\u00e8re (1758)|''Chim\u00e8re'']], sailing into the river and forcing the British to scuttle several ships,<ref name=cunat40>Cunat, p.40</ref> notably [[HMS Rose (1757)|HMS ''Rose'']].\n\nOn 1 March 1780, [[Louis XVI of France|Louis XVI]] granted Suffren a 1,500 [[French livre]] pension in recognition of his services.<ref name=cunat41>Cunat, p.41</ref> In April, Suffren was given command of the [[74-gun]] {{ship|French ship|Z\u00e9l\u00e9|1764|2}}, part of a two-ship squadron along with [[French ship Vengeur du Peuple|''Marseillais'']], under Captain [[Fran\u00e7ois-Hector d'Albert de Rions|d'Albert de Rions]].<ref name=cunat42>Cunat, p.42</ref> They set sail on 19 May 1780 to patrol off [[Portugal]], and joined up with a division under Rear-Admiral [[Antoine Hilarion de Beausset|de Beausset]] in [[Cadiz]] on 17 June.<ref name=\"Diaz11\">Diaz de Soria, ''Le Marseillois'', p. 11.</ref> He then joined up with a combined Franco-Spanish fleet under Admiral [[Luis de C\u00f3rdova y C\u00f3rdova]]. On 9 August, the fleet intercepted a large British convoy, leading to the [[Action of 9 August 1780]]. The British escort, comprising the 74-gun {{HMS|Ramillies|1763|6}}, under Captain Sir [[John Moutray]], and the frigates [[HMS Thetis (1773)|''Thetis'']] and [[HMS Southampton (1757)|''Southampton'']], fled before the vastly superior combined fleet. Suffren attempted to give chase, but the [[copper sheathing]] of the British warship gave them a decisive advantage, and he abandoned the pursuit to help with the capture of the merchantmen.<ref name=cunat42 />{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}} After the battle, Suffren wrote a letter to [[Antoine de Sartine]], [[Secretary of State of the Navy (France)|Secretary of State of the Navy]], to advocate for the French Navy to copper is own ships.<ref name=cunat44>Cunat, p.44</ref><ref>The full text of Suffren's memorandum on copper sheating is quoted in Cunat, p.353-354</ref>\n\n===Campaign in the Indian Ocean===\n{{Main|Franco-Indian alliances}}\n\nWith the outbreak of the [[Fourth Anglo-Dutch War]], France and the [[Dutch Republic]] found themselves allied against the [[Kingdom of Great Britain]]. The Dutch expected the British to send an expeditionary force to try and capture their [[Dutch Cape Colony]], and Suffren was given command of a 5-ship squadron to reinforce it. The task force comprised the 74-gun [[French ship H\u00e9ros (1778)|''H\u00e9ros'']] (under Suffren) and [[French ship Annibal (1778)|''Annibal'']] (under [[Achille de Tr\u00e9migon|Tr\u00e9mignon]]), and the 64-gun [[French ship Art\u00e9sien|''Art\u00e9sien'']] (under Cardaillac), [[French ship Sphinx (1776)|''Sphinx'']] (under du Chilleau) and [[French ship Vengeur (1765)|''Vengeur'']] (under Forbin), <ref name=cunat48>Cunat, p.48</ref> as well as the 16-gun corvette [[French corvette Fortune (1780)|''Fortune'']] (under Captain de Lusignan), and seven transports <ref name=cunat49>Cunat, p.49</ref> carrying the [[107th Infantry Regiment (France)|R\u00e9giment de Pondich\u00e9ry]], under Brigadier General [[Thomas Conway]].<ref name=cunat63>Cunat, p.63</ref>\n\n==== Battle of Porto Praya ====\n{{Main|Battle of Porto Praya}}\nThe squadron departed Brest on 22 March 1781. En route, ''Art\u00e9sien'', which had originally been appointed to a shorter mission, found herself short on water, and Captain de Cardaillac requested permission to resupply at [[Santiago, Cape Verde|Santiago]]. Suffren gave permission but, unwilling to scatter his forces, ordered his entire squadron to move into [[Praia Harbor|Praia Harbour]]. Arriving there at 0830 the morning of 16 April, ''Art\u00e9sien'' spotted five British warship at anchor; she turned, signalling \"enemy ships in sight\". Understanding that random chance had put him in contact with [[George Johnstone (royal navy)|George Johnstone]]'s squadron,<ref name=hennequin294>Hennequin, p.294</ref> and disregarding neutrality laws,<ref name=Monaque-pon-87 />{{refn|Several authors attribute Suffren's disregard for neutrality law to his experience at the [[Battle of Lagos]], 20 years earlier.<ref name=Monaque-pon-87 /><ref name=cunat50 /><ref name=hennequin294 />|group=Note}} Suffren ordered an immediate attack.<ref name=cunat50>Cunat, p.50</ref> At 1000, Suffren's squadron attacked, precipitating the [[Battle of Porto Praya]]. Having scattered and desorganised Johnstone's forces, Suffren rushed to The Cape, and arrived at [[Simon's Bay]] on 21 June. <ref name=cunat62>Cunat, p.62</ref> The R\u00e9giment de Pondich\u00e9ry landed and started fortifying the Cape colony against attacks from land and from the sea, while the fleet repaired its ships and had its sick given medical attention in hospitals ashore.<ref name=cunat63 />\n\nJohnstone arrived in the morning of 21 July, left two frigates to watch the bay, and sailed on to [[Saldanha Bay]].<ref name=cunat63 /> On 24 July, Suffren set sail with four ships,{{refn|''Annibal'' was in need of more extensive repair to her rigging:<ref name=cunat65>Cunat, p.65</ref> after losing her masts at Porto Praya, she had done the rest of the journey in two of ''Sphinx''.<ref name=hennequin295>Hennequin, p.295</ref> |group=Note}} chased away the British frigates, and patroled the area around the Cape to acertain the intentions of the British. Satisfied that Johnstone had renounced attacking the Cape colony, he resupplied and sailed to [[Isle de France (Mauritius)|Isle de France]]<ref group=Note>The present-day [[Mauritius]]</ref> with the rest of the squadron, arriving on 28 July.<ref name=cunat64>Cunat, p.64</ref>\n\n==== Preliminary operations at Isle de France ====\nUntil the oubreak of the Anglo-French War, the French colony of [[Puducherry|Pondich\u00e9ry]] maintained a small squadron squadron under [[Fran\u00e7ois-Jean-Baptiste l'Ollivier de Tronjoli]]{{refn|Sometimes spelt \"Tronjoly\"<ref name=cunat74>Cunat, p.74</ref>|group=Note}}, comprising the 64-gun [[French ship Brillant (1774)|''Brillant'']] (under Tronjoli), the 40-gun frigate [[French frigate Pourvoyeuse (1772)|''Pourvoyeuse'']] (under Captain de Saint-Orens{{refn|Cunats spells \"Saint-Orins\"<ref name=cunat69>Cunat, p.69</ref>|group=Note}}, and three armed merchantmen: the 26-gun corvette [[HMS Sartine (1778)|''Sartine'']] (under du Chayla), the 24-gun [[French frigate Brisson (1767)|''Brisson'']] (under Captain du Ch\u00e9zeau), and the 24-gun [[French corvette Lawriston (1778)|''Lawriston'']].<ref name=cunat69 /> During the [[Siege of Pondicherry (1778)|Siege of Pondicherry]] in 1778, Tronjoli had lost some of his ships and escaped to Isle de France with the survivors, arriving there in late September.<ref name=cunat72>Cunat, p.72</ref> Pondich\u00e9ry fell to the British on 17 October.<ref name=cunat71>Cunat, p.71</ref> With these reinforcements, the island was guarded by the 64-gun ''Brillant'', the 54-gun [[French ship Flamand|''Flamand'']], the frigates ''Pourvoyeuse'' and [[French frigate Consolante (1775)|''Consolante'']], and the smaller [[French corvette Subtile (1777)|''Subtile'']] (a 24-gun corvette), [[French fluyt Elisabeth (1760)|''Elisabeth'']] (a [[fluyt]]) and [[French corvette Sylphide (1763)|''Sylphide'']] (a 12-gun corvette).<ref name=cunat72 /> Furthermore, on 28 December 1778, the 74-gun [[French ship Orient (1756)|''Orient'']]{{refn|Built as a 80-gun, ''Orient'' had been reduced to a 74-gun in early 1766<ref name=Demerliac17>Demerliac, ''1774-1792'', n\u00b022 p.17</ref>|group=Note}} departed Brest under [[Thomas d'Estienne d'Orves]] to reinforce the colony, and on 27 March 1779, so did the 64-gun [[French ship S\u00e9v\u00e8re (1778)|''S\u00e9v\u00e8re'']], under la Palli\u00e8re, escorting the transports ''Hercule'' and ''Trois-Amis'', arriving on 9 August 1779.<ref name=cunat73>Cunat, p.73</ref> With four ships of the line now at his disposal, Tronjoli departed on 6  December 1779 to cruise off the Cape, but to no avail, and he returned to Isle de France on 13 January 1780.<ref name=cunat75>Cunat, p.75</ref> On 3 February 1780, the 64-gun [[French ship Bizarre (1751)|''Bizarre'']] departed Lorient to further reinforce Isle de France.<ref name=cunat81>Cunat, p.81</ref> After it was confirmed that the British had despatched a squadron under [[Edward Hughes (Royal Navy officer)|Admiral Hughes]] in the Indian Ocean, France sent a convoy comprising the 64-gun [[French ship Prot\u00e9e (1772)|''Prot\u00e9e'']] and [[French ship Ajax (1779)|''Ajax'']], and the frigate [[French frigate Charmante (1777)|''Charmante'']] (under Baron de la Haye),<ref name=cunat83>Cunat, p.83</ref> escorting 16 transports ferrying the [[R\u00e9giment d'Austrasie]] under Brigadier Duchemin de Chenneville.<ref name=cunat82>Cunat, p.82</ref> En route, the convoy encountered a British squadron under Admiral [[George Rodney]], yielding the [[Action of 24 February 1780]] in which ''Prot\u00e9e'' sacrificed herself and tree smaller transports to lure the British away from the others. ''Charmante'' returned to Lorient to bring the news of the engagement, while the other survivors sailed on to Isle de France. By 1780, Tronjoly was recalled to France, leaving d'Orves in command with a total of six ships of the line at his disposal.<ref name=cunat83 />\n\nSuffren arrived at Isle de France on 25 October 1781.<ref name=cunat94>Cunat, p.94</ref><ref name=hennequin297>Hennequin, p.297</ref> The island had been selected as the base for French operations in the Indian Ocean, falling under the overall command of [[Marquis de Bussy-Castelnau]].<ref name=cunat95>Cunat, p.95</ref>\n\nOn 7 December 1781, d'Orves led a 27-ship fleet to Ceylon, with his flag on ''Orient''. He had 11 ships of the line, 3 frigates and 3 corvettes at his disposal. En route, d'Orves changed his objectif from [[Trincomalee]] to [[Madras]].<ref name=cunat97>Cunat, p.97</ref><ref group=Note>Present-day [[Chennai]]</ref> On 19 January, ''S\u00e9v\u00e8re'' detected a strange sail, and d'Orves detached ''H\u00e9ros'' and ''Art\u00e9sien'' to investigate. Suffren closed in, making signals according to tables captured at Porto Praya on the East Indiaman [[Hinchinbrooke (1780 ship)|''Hinchinbrooke'']], until the ship made signals that he was unable to answer. A chase ensued, and with the night Suffren abandonned the pursuit to rejoin the fleet. On 21, the fleet encountered the same ship again, and again detached ''H\u00e9ros'', ''Art\u00e9sien'' and ''Vengeur'', but this time with other ships deploying as to ensure communication between the pursuers and the main body of the fleet, allowing Suffren to press on his chase. Suffren caught up with his quarry on 22 around noon and forced her to surrender. She was the 50-gun [[HMS Hannibal (1779)|HMS ''Hannibal'']], under Captain Christy, which the French pressed into their service as ''Petit Annibal''.<ref name=cunat99>Cunat, p.99</ref>\n\n==== Battle of Sadras ====\n{{Main|Battle of Sadras}}\nIn the following days, d'Orves' failing health deteriorated to the point where he was not fit for duty, and he delegated command to Suffren.<ref name=cunat100>Cunat, p.100</ref> The French intended to surprise the British ships anchored in the roads of Madras. The fleet arrived North of Madras on 5 February 1782, and its light units started praying on coastal merchantmen and capturing cargo of rice.<ref name=cunat101>Cunat, p.101</ref> However, the [[monsoon]] caused strong winds from the South which trapped the French North of Madras, while at the same time favouring the return of Hughes' squadron from Ceylon to Madras.<ref name=cunat102>Cunat, p.102</ref> Upon Hughes' arrival, [[George Macartney, 1st Earl Macartney|Lord Macartney]] warned him of the presence of the French squadron, and Hughes anchored his ships under the protection of [[Fort St. George, India|Fort St. George]] and [[George Town, Chennai|Black Town]]. On 9 February 1782, Hughes received reinforcements with the arrival of a squadron comprising the 64-gun [[HMS Monmouth (1772)|HMS ''Monmouth'']], the [[74-gun]] [[HMS Hero (1759)|''Hero'']], the 50-gun [[HMS Isis (1774)|''Isis'']] and the armed transport ''Manilla'', under [[James Alms]]. \n\nD'Orves died the same day at 1600. Suffren re-appointed his captains to the ships of the squadon: Captain de Lapalli\u00e8re{{refn|Sometimes spelt \"la Palli\u00e8re\"<ref name=cunat104 />|group=Note}} took command of ''Orient'' and [[Chevalier de Villeneuve-Cillart|Cillart]] that of ''S\u00e9v\u00e8re''; Captain [[Justin Bonaventure Morard de Galles|Morard de Galles]], of ''Pourvoyeuse'', and Lieutenant de Ruyter, in temporary command of ''Petit Annibal'', exchanged their positions; [[Jean Andr\u00e9 de Pas de Beaulieu|Beaulieu]] went on ''Bellone'';<ref name=cunat103>Cunat, p.103</ref>  Tromelin (the Younger) took on ''Subtile''; and Galifet took ''Sylphide''. General Duchemin transfered from ''Orient'' to ''H\u00e9ros''.<ref name=cunat104>Cunat, p.104</ref>\n\nOn 14 February, usual monsoon wind from the North-East resumed, allowing Suffren's squadron to sail South. In the evening, [[French frigate Fine (1779)|''Fine'']], under Perrier de Salvert, came in view of Madras harbour and Hughes' squadron. Seeing Hugues anchored in a very strong defensive position, Suffren decided to sail off the coast, <ref name=cunat105>Cunat, p.105</ref> but to his surprise, Hugues left the safety of the forts and gave chase.<ref name=cunat106>Cunat, p.106</ref> Suffren deployed a frigate screen to warn his squadron of Hugues' moves, but during the night ''Pourvoyeuse'' drifted away from the fleet due to a navigation error, while  ''Fine'' lost sight of the British ships, and both thus failed to keep Suffren appraised of Hughes's position.<ref name=cunat108>Cunat, p.108</ref> In the morning, signals from ''Fine'' informed Suffren that HMS ''Montmouth'', ''Hero'', ''Isis'', ''Aigle'' and ''Burford'' where approaching the French transports. Suffren rushed with his warships to protect the convoy, and Hughes ordered his ships to regroup and form a [[line of battle]].<ref name=cunat109>Cunat, p.109</ref> In the morning of 17 February, the fleets were about 6 km apart{{refn|one [[League (unit)|League]] and a half<ref name=cunat109 />|group=Note}}, the British forming a line and had captured ''Lawriston'', while the French were scattered due to an error in interpreting night signals. Suffren formed a line without consideration for the order of battle,<ref name=cunat111>Cunat, p.111</ref> and at 1500 he closed in within gun range, starting the [[Battle of Sadras]].\n\nSuffren sustained about 30 men killed and 100 wounded,<ref name=cunat115>Cunat, p.115</ref> and light damage to his riggings.<ref name=cunat116>Cunat, p.116</ref> At 1900 he broke contact.<ref name=cunat115 />\n\n==== Battle of Providien ====\n{{Main|Battle of Providien}}\nSuffren returned to [[Pondich\u00e9ry]], where he arrived on 19 February 1782 and learned that the British squadron was heading for [[Trincomalee]]. After consulting [[Hyder Ali]], he decided not to land his troops in Pondich\u00e9ry, and rather to head for [[Parangipettai|Porto Nove]], where he arrived on 23 February. <ref name=hennequin299>Hennequin, p.299</ref> Hyder Ali despatched [[Andr\u00e9 Piveron de Morlat]], the French ambassador, to act as an intermediary between Suffren and himself, along with two of his officiers. Suffren negotiated an agreement that French troops would retain their own command; that a 4,000-man cavalry and 6,000-man infantry force would reinforce them; and that they be paid 24 [[Lakh]] rupee a year.<ref name=hennequin302>Hennequin, p.302</ref> Suffren landed his troops at Porto Nove, and departed on 23 March to search for the British fleet.\n\nOn 10 April, the two fleet came into view, and they spent two days in manoeuvers, trying to gain an advantage on the other.<ref name=hennequin302 /> In the morning, ''Fine'' captured a British courier and managed to retrieve the despatches that her captain had thrown overboard, revealing British plans to expel the Dutch from Ceylon.<ref name=cunat127>Cunat, p. 127</ref>   On 12, the [[Battle of Providien]] broke out, leaving both squadrons damaged. Suffren retreated to the safety of the Dutch forts of [[Batticaloa|Batacalo]] to repair, and tend to those members of his crews who were wounded or suffered from scurvy.<ref name=hennequin302 />\n\n==== Battle of Negapatam ====\n{{Main|Battle of Negapatam (1782)}}\nOn 3 June, Suffren departed Batacalo and sailed to [[Cuddalore]], where he received letters from Hyder Ali requesting that he lay siege to [[Nagapattinam]]. The French troops reembarked on their transports, when ''Bellone'', which had been left to patrol, came with news that Hughes' squadron was at Nagapattinam. Suffren ordered an immediate departure and found the British ships anchored when he arrived on 6 July 1782.<ref name=Hennequin303>Hennequin, p.303</ref> Before the battle, Suffren despatched [[French frigate Pourvoyeuse (1772)|''Pourvoyeuse'']] to [[Malacca]], [[HMS Resolution (1771)|''R\u00e9solution'']] to [[Manila]], and [[Fortitude (1780 EIC ship)|''Fortitude'']] and [[Yarmouth (1782 ship)|''Yarmouth'']] to Isle de France, to purchase spare [[Spar (sailing)|spars]], food and ammunition to resupply his fleet. He furtermore kept [[French corvette Sylphide (1763)|''Sylphide'']] and [[French corvette Diligent (1781)|''Diligent'']] handy to bring news of the outcome of the battle to Isle de France.<ref name=cunat164>Cunat, p.164</ref>\n\nThe [[Battle of Negapatam (1782)|Battle of Negapatam]] ensued. The two fleet exchanged fire to over 4 hours, until Hughes retreated.<ref name=Hennequin303 /> During the battle,  Captain [[Chevalier de Villeneuve-Cillart|Cillart]],<ref name=threedeck-cillart>{{cite web |title=de Cillart (Chevalier de Cillart) |url=https://threedecks.org/index.php?display_type=show_crewman&id=38982 |website=Three Deck's Forum}}</ref>{{refn|Also known as Villeneuve-Cilart <ref name=threedeck-cillart />|group=Note}} captain of ''S\u00e9v\u00e8re'', panicked and [[Striking the colors|struck his colours]] but one of the officers, named Dieu and Kerlero de Rosbo,<ref name=roche414>Roche, p.414</ref> refused to surrender and resumed firing. [[HMS Sultan (1775)|HMS ''Sultan'']] had stopped to launch her boats and take possession of ''S\u00e9v\u00e8re'', and sustained serious damage when the broadsides of ''S\u00e9v\u00e8re'' suddenly [[Raking fire|raked]] her. <ref name=Hennequin305>Hennequin, p.305</ref> Seeing his hand forced, Cillart ordered his flag hoisted again. <ref name=Hennequin306>Hennequin, p.306</ref>{{refn|When known in France, the anecdote yielded the pun that \"Villeneuve-Cilart wanted to surrender, but \"God\" (''Dieu'', the name of the insubordinate officer) would not allow it\".<ref name=Hennequin306 />|group=Note}}\n\nSuffren cruised off Nagapattinam to observe the moves of the British ships, and seeing them idle, returned to Cuddalore to repair.<ref name=Hennequin304>Hennequin, p.304</ref> On the way, [[HMS Rodney (1781) |HMS ''Rodney'']] joined up as [[Cartel (ship)|cartel]] with ''H\u00e9ros'', with Captain James Watt of [[HMS Sultan (1775)|HMS ''Sultan'']]<ref name=cunat177>Cunat, p.177</ref> bringing a letter from Hughes demanding that Suffren hand over ''S\u00e9v\u00e8re'' after her surrender. Suffren answered that he was unaware that ''S\u00e9v\u00e8re'' had surrendered and promised to launch an investigation, and also warned that without orders from his government he was not at liberty to give away his ships.<ref name=Hennequin304 /> \n\nFollowing the incident with ''S\u00e9v\u00e8re'', Suffren relieved Cillart of duty and sent him back to Isle de France to be returned to France and [[court-martial]]ed.<ref name=cunat179>Cunat, p. 179</ref> He also dismissed Maureville of ''Art\u00e9sien'',  Forbin of ''Vengeur'' and De Ruyter of ''Pourvoyeuse'', as well as three more junior officers.<ref name=Hennequin306 /> Command of ''Art\u00e9sien'' went to [[Armand de Saint-F\u00e9lix|Saint-F\u00e9lix]]; that of ''Vengeur'' went to [[Louis-Hyacinte de Cavelier de Cuverville|Cuverville]], himself replaced by Lieutenant [[\u00c9l\u00e9onor Jacques Marie Stanislas P\u00e9rier de Salvert|P\u00e9rier de Salvert]] at the command of ''Flamand''; Lieutenant Maureville de Langle was promoted to the command of ''S\u00e9v\u00e8re''; ''Brillant'' went to [[Jean Andr\u00e9 de Pas de Beaulieu|Beaulieu]], himself replaced on ''Bellone'' by Chevalier de Pierre-Vert; and Lieutenant de Beaumont le Ma\u00eetre received command of ''Ajax''.<ref name=cunat180>Cunat, p.180</ref>\n\n==== Battle of Trincomalee ====\n{{Main|Battle of Trincomalee}}\n[[File:Suffren meeting with Haider Ali, 26 july 1782 engraved by J B Morret 1789.jpg|thumb|Suffren meeting with [[Hyder Ali]] on 26 July 1782. Engraving by [[Jean-Baptiste Morret]], 1789.]]\nOn 25 July, Hyder Ali arrived at [[Bahour]] under the gun salutes of the fortress and the whole French squadron. The next day, a 500-man cavalry troop under General Ghulam Ali Khan escorted Suffren, six of his captains and several officers to the encampment of Hyder Ali's army for a meeting with him.<ref name=Hennequin306 /> Suffren announced that Bussy-Castelnau had arrived to Isle de France with 6 ships of the line, 2 frigates and transports carrying 5,000 soldiers. He also informed Hyder Ali that a French frigate had intercepted a British schooner carrying Colonal Horn to Nagapattinam. Hyder Ali responded with luxurious gifts to Suffren and his officers, or with gifts represented by their equivalent value in rupees. He then ajourned the meeting until the next day.<ref name=Hennequin308>Hennequin, p.308</ref>{{refn|Suffren received 10,000 rupees symbolising the gift of an elephant, which would have been inconvenient on ''H\u00e9ros''; his officers received 1,000 symbolising horses, for the same reason.<ref name=Hennequin308 />|group=Note}}\n\nOn 27, Hyder Ali invited Suffren and Piveron to a private dinner, with European-style seating in deference to his guests.<ref name=Hennequin309>Hennequin, p.309</ref>{{refn|The previous day, Suffren, who was overweight, had suffered from the Indian-style seating and Hyder Ali had graciously bent the etiquette to accomodate him.<ref name=Hennequin308 />|group=Note}} Suffren reported on the battles against Hughes, and they reviewed plans of operations against the British. Hyder Ali was especially concerned by British advance on the [[Malabar Coast]] and the risk that the [[Maratha Empire]] would switch sides, ally with the British and start a war with Mysore.{{refn|The [[Maratha\u2013Mysore War]] was to start three years later.|group=Note}}\n\nMeanwhile, the French squadron was effecting repairs, especially to its rigging, and ''Pourvoyeuse'' sailed to [[Malacca]] to pick up [[Spar (sailing)|spars]].<ref name=Hennequin311>Hennequin, p.311</ref> In early August, Suffren learnt that the British fleet had departed Nagapattinam and was embarking troops in Madras, bound for an unknown destination. Suffren departed at once for [[Tharangambadi]] in the hope of undercovering the British plans. Failing to do so, he sailed to Batticaloa, where he arrived on 8 August to find ''Consolante'', arrived from Isle de France three days earlier. From ''Consolante'', Suffren learnt that two French ships of the line escorting 8 transports were anchored at [[Galle]], waiting to join up with him. Suffren had sent a light ship to Trincomalee, which returned announcing that the British ship were not there. Suffren then decided to lay siege to Trincomalee.<ref name=Hennequin311 />\n\nOn 21 August, the two ships of the convoy arrived. Suffren had ammunition from the convoy distributed among his warships to replenish their magazines, and explained his intentions to the captains. <ref name=Hennequin311 /> The same day, the cutter ''L\u00e9zard'' arrived from France, bringing despatches. The letter notably carried official approval of Suffren's conduct at the Battle of Porto Praya, and granted the requests he had made to appoint his officers. Furthermore, a letter from [[Emmanuel de Rohan-Polduc]], [[List of Grand Masters of the Knights Hospitaller|Grand Master of the Knights Hospitaller]], informed him that he was promoted to Bailiff of the [[Sovereign Military Order of Malta]].<ref name=Hennequin312>Hennequin, p.312</ref>\n\nOn 25 August, the fleet set sail and formed a battle line, soon arriving in view of the forts of Trincomalee. 2,000 men quickly landed, with siege artillery, ammunition and three days worth of rations. By 29, the French had completed their siege battery emplacements, and they started bombarding the fort. On 30, at 0900, Suffren sent a message to [[Fort Ostenburg]] to negotiate its capitulation. The British surrendered the fort in exchange for its 1,000-man garrison to be sent to Madras.<ref name=Hennequin312 />\n\nOn 3 September, the British fleet arrived. Suffren reembarked his troops and moved to intercept, leading to the [[Battle of Trincomalee]].<ref name=Hennequin314>Hennequin, p.314</ref> The French line fought desorganised, especially after ''Vengeur'' caught fire and have to distance herself from other ships. The flag of ''H\u00e9ros'' was shot away by British fire and Suffren had new French ensigns hoisted to continue the fight. After one hour and a half, night fell and the battle ended. Suffren was furious at the conduct of his captains, whom he accused of abandonning him.<ref name=Hennequin316>Hennequin, p.316</ref> The next day, the British fleet had disappeared, and Suffren returned to Trincomalee, where he arrived in the evening of 7 September 1782.<ref name=Hennequin317>Hennequin, p.317</ref> \n\n==== Battle of Cuddalore ====\n{{Main|Battle of Cuddalore (1783)}}\nWhen the French squadron arrived at Trincomalee in the evening of 7 September 1782 after the Battle of Trincomalee, its ships were seriously damaged. ''H\u00e9ros'', in particular, was leaking and had lost her foremast and mainmast. The ships anchored to effect repairs, which the crew completed in two weeks. Meanwhile, Suffren received news that Hyder Ali had left Cuddalore with his army to fight in the North, leaving the city vulnerable to a British attack fom Madras. As Cuddalore was a crucial supply depot, it was imperative for Suffren to protect it. Suffren departed Trincomalee on 1 October to reinforce Cuddalore, <ref name=Hennequin317 /> arriving on 4 October. The expected British attack did not happen, and on 12 October, the change in monsoon forced both fleets to shelter in harbour. Hughes anchored at Bombay, <ref name=Hennequin318>Hennequin, p.318</ref> while Suffren chose to sail to [[Aceh]]. By choosing Aceh, Suffren avoided both being driven away from the battlefield as he would have by chosing Isle de France, and the climate of Trincomalee which he feared would be detrimental to his crew.<ref name=Hennequin318>Hennequin, p.318</ref>\n\nThe French squadron left Cuddalore on 15 October 1782 and arrived at Aceh on 1 November. ''Pourvoyeuse'' and ''Bellone'' arrived shortly after with spare parts, and the fleet spent the following weeks tending to the sick and effecting repairs.<ref name=Hennequin319>Hennequin, p.319</ref> After a while, a corvette arrived from Isle de France, bringing news that a 3-ship squadron under [[Antoine de Thomassin de Peynier]] was about to arrive, escorting a convoy ferrying troops and ammunitions, as well as Bussy-Castelnau.<ref name=Hennequin320>Hennequin, p.320</ref>\n\nSuffren's fleet set sail on 20 December to return to Coromandel. On the way, it raided the British colony of [[Ganjam]], destroying a number of merchantmen. On 12 january 1783, the frigate [[HMS Coventry (1757)|HMS ''Coventry'']], unaware of the presence of the French fleet and mistaking its ships for East Indiamen, approached and had to surrender. From the prisoners, Suffren learnt of  Hyder Ali's death. The fleet continued to Cuddalore, arriving there on 1 February.<ref name=Hennequin320 /> Peynier's squadron of 3 ships and 1 frigate arrived shortly afterwards with 30 transports, survivors of a much larger convoy that had lost a number of ships to the elements and to the British. <ref name=Hennequin321>Hennequin, p.321</ref>\n\nWith the return of favourable weather, Suffren expected and feared Hughes' attack, as his own ships were either damaged after long cruises, or had at best only received field repair at Aceh. He therefore quickly landed his troops at Cuddalore and set sail for Trincomalee. Unfavourable winds made progression difficult and as Suffren's squadron entered the bay, ''Fine'' reported 17 sails closing in.<ref name=Hennequin321 /> The French squadron retreated into the safety of Trincomalee and started repairing. <ref name=Hennequin322>Hennequin, p.322</ref>\n\nOn 24 May, Hughes' squadron passed off Trincomalee. A few days later, a ship brought letters from Bussy-Castelnau announcing that Cuddalore was besieged and blockaded.<ref name=Hennequin322 /> Suffren departed Trincomalee on 11 June 1783 and passed off Tharangambadi on 16, when the frigate screen signaled 18 ships in view. Suffren transfered onto the frigate [[French frigate Cl\u00e9op\u00e2tre (1781)|''Cl\u00e9op\u00e2tre'']] to personnally reconnoitre the situation. The two fleets approached each other in the evening manoeuvered without engaging. In the morning, the French found themselves at the entrance of Cuddalore Bay, while the British squadron was further off at sea.<ref name=Hennequin323>Hennequin, p.323</ref> Suffren anchored his ships and spent the night reinforcing his crew with 1,200 soldiers from ashore.<ref name=Hennequin324>Hennequin, p.324</ref> On 18 June, Suffren set sail and the two squadrons chased each other for two days, trying to gain an advantage. Finally, on 20, the two fleets came in contact and engaged, starting the [[Battle of Cuddalore (1783)|Battle of Cuddalore]] at 1530. <ref name=Hennequin324 /> \n\nOn 25, Hughes retreated to Madras,<ref name=Hennequin326>Hennequin, p.326</ref> and on 29, a British frigate came as a cartel,<ref name=Hennequin327>Hennequin, p.327</ref> bringing news of the preliminary agreements to the [[Treaty of Paris (1783)|Treaty of Paris]] that had been signed on 9 February 1783, and Hughes' offer of a cease-fire. Suffren accepted. On 25 July, the frigate [[French frigate Surveillante (1778)|''Surveillante'']] arrived from Europe with news of the [[Peace of Paris (1783)|Peace of Paris]] and orders to Suffren to return to France, leaving 5 ships under Peynier in the Indian Ocean.<ref name=Hennequin328>Hennequin, p.328</ref>\n\n=== Post-War ===\nWith the war over, both the French fleet under Suffren and the British fleet under Hughes returned to Europe. On his way, Suffren called the Cape of Good Hope, and had stayed there for a few days when Hughes' squadron arrived, with unfavourable winds. [[HMS Exeter (1763)|HMS ''Exeter'']] ran aground,<ref name=cunat338>Cunat, p.338</ref> and both the British and French ships launched their boats to provide assistance.<ref name=Hennequin329>Hennequin, p.329</ref>\n\nSuffren arrived at Toulon on 26 March 1784. Summoned to Versailles, he was received by Navy Minister [[Charles Eug\u00e8ne Gabriel de La Croix|Castrie]] and by Louis XVI, and much celebrated. <ref name=Hennequin329 /> A fourth position of [[Vice-Admiral]] was created especially for Suffren, the decree stipulating that it would be suppressed after his death.<ref name=Hennequin330>Hennequin, p.330</ref>\n\nIn October 1787, with the implementation of the [[Eden Agreement]], tensions again flared up between France and England, and it was feared that a new conflict was looming. As a precaution, Louix XVI ordered the Brest squadron be readied, and he appointed Suffren to command it, leaving him the choice of his captains. As he prepared for the journey to Brest, Suffren's health suddenly declined. He died in Paris on 8 December 1788.<ref name=Hennequin331>Hennequin, p.331</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n=== Assessment ===\nSuffren was generally recognised as an able commander. The [[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Eleventh Edition|''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica'' Eleventh Edition]] called him \"perhaps the ablest sea-commander that France ever produced'.<ref>{{Cite EB1911 |wstitle=Hughes, Sir Edward |volume=13 |page=660}}</ref> In ''[[The Influence of Sea Power upon History]]'', [[Alfred Thayer Mahan|Mahan]] writes:\n\n{{quote|The military situation... demanded first the disabling of the hostile fleet, next the capture of certain strategic ports. That this diagnosis was correct is as certain as that it reversed the common French maxims, which would have put the port first and the fleet second as objectives.<ref>Mahan, A.T., ''The Influence of Sea Power Upon History 1660\u20131783, p. 433 {{ISBN|0-486-25509-3}}</ref>}}\n\n[[R\u00e9mi Monaque]] offers a more nuanced assessment, finding Suffren an aggressive and innovative commander comparable to Ruyter and Nelson,<ref name=Monaque-pon-91>Monaque, ''A Precursor of Nelson'', p.91</ref> but also one whose lack of didactic qualities and social graces made misunderstood and disliked by his captains, and thus failed to develop its full potential. <ref name=Monaque-pon-90>Monaque, ''A Precursor of Nelson'', p.90</ref>\n\n=== Monuments and memorials ===\n{{see also|French ship Suffren}}\n[[French ship Suffren|Eight ships]] of the French Navy have been named ''Suffren'' in honour of Suffren de Saint Tropez. \n\nA number of streets and avenues through France are named in Suffren's honour. In Paris, the {{ill|Avenue de Suffren|fr}} runs alongside the [[Champ de Mars]].\n\n{{Gallery\n |title=Depictions of Suffren\n |align=center\n |BailliDeSuffrenByBatoni.jpg|Suffren, by [[Pompeo Batoni]].\n |Saint-Tropez Suffren (1)-white.jpg|Suffren's statue in [[Saint Tropez]].\n |Lestevenon-buys-1784.jpg|The envoys [[Mattheus Lestevenon]] and [[Gerard Brantsen]] presenting vice-admiral Pierre Andr\u00e9 Bailly de Suffren de Saint Tropez with a golden sword in 1784\n |Suffren mg 7244.jpg|Bust of Suffren by [[Isidore-Hippolyte Brion|Brion]], on display at [[Paris naval museum]].\n}}\n\n== Sources and references ==\n''' Notes'''\n{{Reflist|group=Note}}\n\n'''References'''\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n''' Bibliography'''\n* {{EB1911|wstitle=Suffren Saint Tropez, Pierre Andr\u00e9 de|volume=26}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Cunat |first1=Charles |authorlink1=Charles Cunat|title=Histoire du Bailli de Suffren |date=1852 |publisher=A. Marteville et Lefas |location=Rennes |pages=447 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-jkBAAAAQAAJ}}\n* {{cite book|title=La Marine de Louis XVI: Nomenclature des Navires Fran\u00e7ais de 1774 \u00e0 1792|last=Demerliac|first=Alain|year=2004|publisher=\u00c9ditions Ancre|isbn=2-906381-23-3|language=French}}\n* {{cite book|title=Suffren et le temps de Vergennes|last=Glanchant|first=Roger|year=1976|location=Paris|language=French}}\n* {{cite book|title=Biographie maritime ou notices historiques sur la vie et les campagnes des marins c\u00e9l\u00e8bres fran\u00e7ais et \u00e9trangers|last=Hennequin|first=Joseph Fran\u00e7ois Gabriel|author-link=Joseph Fran\u00e7ois Gabriel Hennequin|year=1835|publisher=Regnault \u00e9diteur|location=Paris|url=http://